# ===================================================================
# VERCEL ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES TEMPLATE
# ===================================================================
#
# Copy these variables into Vercel Dashboard:
# Settings → Environment Variables → Add New
#
# IMPORTANT:
# - For each variable, select ALL THREE environments:
#   ☑ Production
#   ☑ Preview
#   ☑ Development
# - Replace placeholder values with your actual values
# - NEVER commit actual values to Git
# ===================================================================

# -------------------------------------------------------------------
# REQUIRED: Base44 Configuration
# -------------------------------------------------------------------

# Your Base44 Application ID
# Find this in your Base44 dashboard
VITE_BASE44_APP_ID=your_actual_base44_app_id_here

# Base44 Backend URL
# Default: https://api.base44.com
VITE_BASE44_BACKEND_URL=https://api.base44.com

# Base44 Functions Version
# Default: prod
VITE_BASE44_FUNCTIONS_VERSION=prod

# -------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTIONAL: Additional Configuration
# -------------------------------------------------------------------

# ELORA External API Key (if used)
# Only needed if you're calling ELORA API directly from frontend
# VITE_ELORA_API_KEY=your_elora_api_key_here

# Analytics Tracking ID (if using Google Analytics)
# VITE_GA_TRACKING_ID=UA-XXXXXXXXX-X

# Sentry DSN (if using error tracking)
# VITE_SENTRY_DSN=https://xxxxx@sentry.io/xxxxx

# Environment Name (helpful for debugging)
# VITE_ENVIRONMENT=production

# ===================================================================
# HOW TO ADD TO VERCEL
# ===================================================================
#
# Method 1: Via Vercel Dashboard (Recommended)
# ----------------------------------------------
# 1. Go to https://vercel.com/dashboard
# 2. Select your project (elora-compliance-portal)
# 3. Click "Settings" tab
# 4. Click "Environment Variables" in sidebar
# 5. For each variable above:
#    a. Click "Add New"
#    b. Name: Copy variable name (e.g., VITE_BASE44_APP_ID)
#    c. Value: Enter your actual value
#    d. Environment: Select all three (Production, Preview, Development)
#    e. Click "Save"
# 6. After adding all variables, redeploy:
#    - Go to "Deployments" tab
#    - Click "..." on latest deployment
#    - Click "Redeploy"
#
# Method 2: Via Vercel CLI
# ------------------------
# vercel env add VITE_BASE44_APP_ID
# (Follow prompts to enter value and select environments)
#
# Method 3: Bulk Import (Advanced)
# ---------------------------------
# Create a file named .env.local with your values, then:
# vercel env pull
#
# ===================================================================
# IMPORTANT NOTES
# ===================================================================
#
# 1. Variable Naming Convention:
#    - Frontend variables MUST start with VITE_
#    - Example: VITE_BASE44_APP_ID ✅
#    - Example: BASE44_APP_ID ❌ (won't be exposed to frontend)
#
# 2. Security:
#    - Never commit .env files with real values
#    - Never expose sensitive keys in frontend code
#    - Use environment variables for all secrets
#
# 3. After Adding Variables:
#    - Always redeploy after adding/changing variables
#    - Variables are only applied to new deployments
#    - Existing deployments keep old variable values
#
# 4. Testing:
#    - Add variables to "Preview" environment to test in PRs
#    - Add to "Development" to use with `vercel dev` locally
#    - Add to "Production" for live deployment
#
# ===================================================================
# WHERE TO FIND YOUR VALUES
# ===================================================================
#
# VITE_BASE44_APP_ID:
#   - Check your local .env file (if you have one)
#   - OR log into Base44 dashboard
#   - OR check Base44 project settings
#
# VITE_BASE44_BACKEND_URL:
#   - Usually: https://api.base44.com
#   - Check Base44 documentation if unsure
#
# VITE_BASE44_FUNCTIONS_VERSION:
#   - Usually: prod
#   - Or: dev, staging (depending on your setup)
#
# ===================================================================
# VERIFICATION AFTER DEPLOYMENT
# ===================================================================
#
# To verify environment variables are working:
#
# 1. Deploy your app to Vercel
# 2. Open your app in browser
# 3. Open browser console (F12)
# 4. Type: console.log(import.meta.env)
# 5. You should see all VITE_ variables listed
#
# If variables are missing:
# - Check they're added in Vercel dashboard
# - Check they start with VITE_
# - Check you selected correct environment
# - Redeploy after adding variables
#
